HashMap in Java

HashMap is one of the most commonly used classes in Java.
It stores data as key-value pairs and provides fast access to data.

How HashMap works (simple idea)

HashMap uses a mechanism called hashing.

👉 What happens:

key → преобразуется в число (hash)
это число определяет, где хранится значение
при поиске — тот же hash помогает быстро найти значение
Key Features
keys are unique
values can be duplicated
allows one null key and multiple null values
not ordered
not thread-safe
Creating a HashMap
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

Map<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
Main Methods
put()
map.put("Apple", 10);
map.put("Banana", 20);

👉 adds or updates value

get()
map.get("Apple"); // 10
remove()
map.remove("Banana");
containsKey() / containsValue()
map.containsKey("Apple");
map.containsValue(10);
size(), isEmpty()
map.size();
map.isEmpty();
Iterating over HashMap
entrySet() (best way)
for (Map.Entry<String, Integer> entry : map.entrySet()) {
    System.out.println(entry.getKey() + " " + entry.getValue());
}
keySet()
for (String key : map.keySet()) {
    System.out.println(key + " " + map.get(key));
}
Internal Structure (important idea)
data stored in buckets
collisions can happen (two keys → same bucket)
Java handles collisions using:
linked list
or tree (since Java 8)

👉 this keeps operations fast

Performance
Operation	Complexity
put()	O(1) average
get()	O(1) average
remove()	O(1) average

Worst case: O(n), but rare

When to use HashMap

Use it when:

you need fast lookup
you work with key-value data
order does NOT matter
When NOT to use
when order matters → use LinkedHashMap
when sorting needed → use TreeMap
in multi-threading → use ConcurrentHashMap
Summary
HashMap stores key → value
very fast (O(1))
no order
allows one null key
most commonly used Map implementation
